4 Group Objectives
4.1 Environment Management
4.1.1 How do we move away from working in a singular D365 development
environment?
4.1.2 What architectural design patterns are required to achieve
such a solution, and what resources can we reuse from NGR’s
DevOps repository?
4.1.3 Does the ideal environmental management solution marry well
with the ideal fast route to production pipeline?†
4.2 Test Automation
4.2.1 What criteria will need to be met in order to pass through
pull requests based on test automation suite results alone?
4.2.2 How do we reach a world where tests are being submitted
alongside pull requests that introduce new functionality?
4.2.3 [Radha Suggestions]
4.3 Routes To Production
4.3.1 How do we move away from large scale ‘big-bang’ drops
4.3.2 What is the ideal delivery pipeline for fasttracking hotfixes to
Production?
4.3.3 Does the ideal fast route to Production pipeline marry well
with the ideal environment management solution?†
All groups will share an objective to compile a list of HMRC-side blockers that
would prevent the progression of the ideal solution. This can then be surfaced
to the relevant stakeholders, providing a runway for remediation heading into
R1.11. Attending BA’s are to transcribe the proposals from each group to inform
any subsequent business plan or Jira backlog generation.
The session will conclude with stand-up presentations from each of the three
teams, with ’yes/no’ answers to whether they have confidently answered each
of their three problem statements. A 1-5 confidence vote will then be taken
answering ”How confident do you feel in being able to implement the presented
ideal solutions by the end of R1.9?”. This will conclude the ways of working
workshop, with an added slot to debrief findings amongst event sponsors and
Cognizant leadership.
† = Groups 1 / 3 to convene and approach final problem statement after lunch break.
